le to a representational level. Photography plays a central role in this representational conflict, by either reproducing or challenging stereotypical narratives of protest. This groundbreaking interdisciplinary analysis of a wide range of practices - amateur and professional - and of previously unpublished archival material will add considerably to students’, researchers’ and scholars’ knowledge of both the visual imagery of political movements and the developing history of photographic representation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4amanchesterhive variable pricing textbooks. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aFrance.  aGenoa.  aMexico.  aanti-globalisation movement.  acultural history.  aindigenous Zapatista movement.  ainternational politics.  amedia studies.  aphotography.  apolitical struggles.  apolitical uprising.  asocial movements.  atheory of art.  avisual culture.1 aMemou, Antigoni, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez9783111283630oZDB-23-MUP40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526130501423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526130501/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-MUPc1986d2013